# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clinical-trials-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In a **blind** or **blinded experiment**, information that could influence participants or investigators is withheld until the experiment is completed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinding is used to reduce or eliminate potential sources of bias, such as participants’ expectations, the observer-expectancy effect, observer bias, confirmation bias, and other cognitive or procedural influences.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinding can be applied to different participants in an experiment, including study subjects, researchers, technicians, data analysts, and outcome assessors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] When multiple groups are blinded simultaneously (for example, both participants and researchers), the design is referred to as a double-blind study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In some cases, blinding is desirable but impractical or unethical.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] For example, it is not possible to blind a participant receiving a physical therapy intervention, or a surgeon performing an operative procedure.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Well-designed clinical protocols therefore aim to maximize the effectiveness of blinding within ethical and practical constraints.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] During the course of an experiment, a participant becomes unblinded if they deduce or otherwise obtain information that has been masked to them.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] For example, a patient who experiences a side effect may correctly guess their treatment, becoming unblinded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding is common in blinded experiments, particularly in pharmacological trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In particular, trials on pain medication and antidepressants are poorly blinded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding that occurs before the conclusion of a study is a source of experimental error, as the bias that was eliminated by blinding is re-introduced.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The CONSORT reporting guidelines recommend that all studies assess and report unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinding is an important tool of the scientific method, and is used in many fields of research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In some fields, such as medicine, it is considered essential.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In clinical research, a trial that is not blinded is called an open trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The first known blind experiment was conducted by the French Royal Commission on Animal Magnetism in 1784 to investigate the claims of mesmerism as proposed by Charles d'Eslon, a former associate of Franz Mesmer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In the investigations, the researchers (physically) blindfolded mesmerists and asked them to identify objects that the experimenters had previously filled with "vital fluid".
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In 1817, the first recorded blind experiment conducted outside a scientific setting compared the musical quality of a Stradivarius violin with that of a guitar-like violin.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A violinist played each instrument while a committee of scientists and musicians listened from another room to avoid prejudice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] An early example of a double-blind protocol was the Nuremberg salt test of 1835 performed by Friedrich Wilhelm von Hoven, Nuremberg's highest-ranking public health official, as well as a close friend of Friedrich Schiller.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] This trial contested the effectiveness of homeopathic dilution.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In 1865, Claude Bernard published his *Introduction to the Study of Experimental Medicine*, which advocated blinding researchers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Bernard's recommendation that an experiment's observer should not know the hypothesis being tested contrasted starkly with the prevalent Enlightenment-era attitude that scientific observation can only be objectively valid when undertaken by a well-educated, informed scientist.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The first study recorded to have a blinded researcher was conducted in 1907 by W.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Webber to investigate the effects of caffeine.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The need to blind researchers became widely recognized in the mid-20th century.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Several biases arise when a study is insufficiently blinded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Patient-reported outcomes may differ when patients are not blinded to their treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Likewise, failure to blind researchers results in observer bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinded data analysts may favor an analysis that supports their existing beliefs (confirmation bias).
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] These biases are typically the result of subconscious influences, and are present even when study participants believe they do not influence them.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In medical research, the terms ***single-blind***, ***double-blind*** and ***triple-blind*** are commonly used to describe blinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] These terms describe experiments in which (respectively) one, two, or three parties are blinded to some information.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] However, the meaning of these terms can vary across studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] CONSORT guidelines state that these terms should no longer be used because they are ambiguous.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] For instance, "double-blind" may mean that the data analysts and patients were blinded; the patients and outcome assessors were blinded; or the patients and those administering the intervention were blinded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The terms also fail to convey the information that was masked and the extent of unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] It is not sufficient to specify the number of parties that have been blinded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] To describe an experiment's blinding, it is necessary to report *who* has been blinded to *what* information, and *how well* each blind succeeded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] "Unblinding" occurs in a blinded experiment when information is revealed to someone to whom it has been masked.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In clinical studies, unblinding may occur unintentionally when a patient deduces their treatment group.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding that occurs before the conclusion of an experiment is a source of bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Some degree of premature unblinding is common in blinded experiments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] When a blind is imperfect, its success is judged on a spectrum with no blind (or complete failure of blinding) on one end, perfect blinding on the other, and poor or good blinding between.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Thus, the common view of studies as blinded or unblinded exemplifies a false dichotomy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The success of blinding is assessed by asking study participants about information that has been masked from them (e.g., whether the participant received the drug or placebo?).
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In a perfectly blinded experiment, the responses should be consistent with no knowledge of the masked information.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] However, if unblinding has occurred, the responses will indicate the degree of unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Since unblinding cannot be measured directly, but must be inferred from participants' responses, its measured value will depend on the nature of the questions asked.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] As a result, it is not possible to objectively measure unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Nonetheless, it is still possible to make informed judgments about the quality of a blinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Poorly blinded studies rank above unblinded studies and below well-blinded studies in the hierarchy of evidence.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Post-study unblinding is the release of masked data upon completion of a study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In clinical studies, post-study unblinding informs subjects of their treatment allocation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Removing a blind upon completion of a study is never mandatory, but is typically performed as a courtesy to study participants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding that occurs after the conclusion of a study is not a source of bias, because data collection and analysis are both complete at this time.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Premature unblinding is any unblinding that occurs before the conclusion of a study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In contrast with post-study unblinding, premature unblinding is a source of bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A code-break procedure dictates when a subject should be unblinded prematurely.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A code-break procedure should allow unblinding only in cases of emergency.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding that occurs in compliance with the code-break procedure is strictly documented and reported.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Premature unblinding may also occur when a participant infers, from the experimental conditions, information that has been masked from him.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A common cause for unblinding is the presence of side effects (or effects) in the treatment group.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In pharmacological trials, premature unblinding can be reduced with the use of an active placebo, which conceals treatment allocation by ensuring the presence of side effects in both groups.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] However, side effects are not the only cause of unblinding; any perceptible difference between the treatment and control groups can contribute to premature unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A problem arises in assessing blinding because asking subjects to guess masked information may prompt them to infer it.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Researchers speculate that this may contribute to premature unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Furthermore, it has been reported that some subjects of clinical trials attempt to determine if they have received an active treatment by gathering information on social media and message boards.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] While researchers counsel patients not to use social media to discuss clinical trials, their accounts are not monitored.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] This behavior is believed to be a source of unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] CONSORT standards and good clinical practice guidelines recommend the reporting of all premature unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In practice, unintentional unblinding is rarely reported.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Bias due to poor blinding tends to favor the experimental group, resulting in inflated effect size and risk of false positives.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Success or failure of blinding is rarely reported or measured; it is implicitly assumed that experiments reported as "blind" are truly blind.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Critics have pointed out that without assessment and reporting, there is no way to know if blinding succeeded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] This shortcoming is especially concerning given that even a small error in blinding can produce a statistically significant result in the absence of any real difference between test groups when a study is sufficiently powered (i.e. statistical significance is not robust to bias).
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] As such, many statistically significant results in randomized controlled trials may be caused by error in blinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Some researchers have called for the mandatory assessment of blinding efficacy in clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinding is considered essential in medicine, but is often difficult to achieve.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] For example, it is difficult to compare surgical and non-surgical interventions in blind trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In some cases, sham surgery may be necessary to blind the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A good clinical protocol ensures that blinding is as adequate as possible within ethical and practical constraints.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Studies of blinded pharmacological trials across diverse domains report high rates of unblinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding has been shown to affect both patients and clinicians.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] This evidence challenges the common assumption that blinding is highly effective in pharmacological trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Unblinding has also been documented in clinical trials outside of pharmacology.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A 2018 meta-analysis found that assessment of blinding was reported in only 23 out of 408 randomized controlled trials for chronic pain (5.6%).
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The study concluded, based on an analysis of pooled data, that the overall quality of blinding was poor and that blinding was "not successful." Additionally, both pharmaceutical sponsorship and the presence of side effects were associated with lower rates of reporting assessment of blinding.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Studies have found evidence of extensive unblinding in antidepressant trials: at least three-quarters of patients were able to guess their treatment assignment correctly.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Better blinding of patients and clinicians reduces effect size.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Researchers concluded that unblinding inflates the effect size in antidepressant trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Some researchers believe that antidepressants are not effective for the treatment of depression and only outperform placebos due to systematic error.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] These researchers argue that antidepressants are just active placebos.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A 2018 study on acupuncture, which used needles that did not penetrate the skin as a sham treatment, found that 68% of patients and 83% of acupuncturists correctly identified their group allocation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] The authors concluded that blinding had failed, but that more advanced placebos may someday enable well-blinded studies in acupuncture.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] It is standard practice in physics to perform blinded data analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Once the data analysis is complete, one may unblind the data.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] A prior agreement to publish the data regardless of the results of the study may be made to prevent publication bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Social science research is particularly prone to observer bias, so it is essential in these fields to properly blind the researchers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In some cases, while blind experiments would be helpful, they are impractical or unethical.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinded data analysis can reduce bias, but is rarely used in social science research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] In a police photo lineup, an officer shows a group of photos to a witness and asks the witness to identify the individual who committed the crime.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Since the officer is typically aware of who the suspect is, they may (subconsciously or consciously) influence the witness to choose the individual that they believe committed the crime.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] There is a growing movement in law enforcement toward a blind procedure in which the officer who shows the photos to the witness does not know the suspect's identity.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Auditions for symphony orchestras take place behind a curtain so that the judges cannot see the performer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blinding the judges to the gender of the performers has been shown to increase the hiring of women.
[src:clinical-trials-design/blinded-experiment] Blind tests can also be used to compare the quality of musical instruments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The **primary endpoint** of a clinical trial is the endpoint for which the trial is powered.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] **Secondary endpoints** are additional endpoints, preferably also pre-specified, for which the trial may not be powered.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] In a general sense, a clinical endpoint is included in the entities of interest in a trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The results of a clinical trial generally indicate the number of people enrolled who reached the pre-determined clinical endpoint during the study interval compared with the overall number of people who were enrolled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Once a patient reaches the endpoint, he or she is generally excluded from further experimental intervention (the origin of the term *endpoint*).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] For example, a clinical trial investigating the ability of a medication to prevent heart attack might use *chest pain* as a clinical endpoint.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Any patient enrolled in the trial who develops chest pain over the course of the trial, then, would be counted as having reached that clinical endpoint.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The results would ultimately reflect the fraction of patients who reached the endpoint of having developed chest pain, compared with the overall number of people enrolled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] A clinical trial will usually define or specify a *primary endpoint* as a measure that will be considered success of the therapy being trialled (e.g. in justifying a marketing approval).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The primary endpoint might be a statistically significant improvement in *overall survival* (OS).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] A trial might also define one or more *secondary endpoints* such as *progression-free-survival* (PFS) that will be measured and are expected to be met.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] A trial might also define *exploratory endpoints* that are less likely to be met.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Clinical endpoints can be obtained from different modalities, such as behavioural or cognitive scores, or biomarkers from Electroencephalography (qEEG), MRI, PET, or biochemical biomarkers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] A cancer study may be powered for overall survival, usually indicating time until death from any cause, or disease-specific survival, where the endpoint is death from disease or death from toxicity.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] These are expressed as a period of time (survival duration) e.g., in months.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Frequently the median is used so that the trial endpoint can be calculated once 50% of subjects have reached the endpoint, whereas calculation of an arithmetical mean can only be done after all subjects have reached the endpoint.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The disease free survival is usually used to analyze the results of the treatment for the localized disease which renders the patient apparently disease free, such as surgery or surgery plus adjuvant therapy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] In the disease-free survival, the event is relapse rather than death.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The people who relapse are still surviving but they are no longer disease-free.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Just as in the survival curves not all patients die, in "disease-free survival curves" not all patients relapse and the curve may have a final plateau representing the patients who didn't relapse after the study's maximum follow-up.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Because the patients survive for at least some time after the relapse, the curve for the actual survival would look better than disease free survival curve.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The Progression Free Survival is usually used in analysing the results of the treatment for the advanced disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The event for the progression free survival is that the disease gets worse or progresses, or the patient dies from any cause.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] *Time to Progression* is a similar endpoint that ignores patients who die before the disease progresses.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The response duration is occasionally used to analyze the results of the treatment for the advanced disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The event is progression of the disease (relapse).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] This endpoint involves selecting a subgroup of the patients.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] It measures the length of the response in those patients who responded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The patients who don't respond aren't included.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Overall survival is based on death from any cause, not just the condition being treated, thus it picks up death from side effects of the treatment, and effects on survival after relapse.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Unlike overall survival, which is based on death from any cause or the condition being treated, the toxic death rate picks up just the deaths that are directly attributable to the treatment itself.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] These rates are generally low to zero as clinical trials are typically halted when toxic deaths occur.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Even with chemotherapy the overall rate is typically under a percent.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] However, the lack of systematic autopsies limits our understanding of deaths due to treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The percentage of treated patients experiencing one or more serious adverse events.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The occurrence of an individual in a trial having reached may necessitate withdrawal from the trial before the target outcome of interest has been fully reached.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] A surrogate endpoint (or *marker*) is a measure of effect of a specific treatment that may correlate with a *real* clinical endpoint but doesn't necessarily have a guaranteed relationship.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The National Institutes of Health (USA) define surrogate endpoint as "a biomarker intended to substitute for a clinical endpoint".
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Some studies will examine the incidence of a *combined endpoint*, which can merge a variety of outcomes into one group.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] For example, the heart attack study above may report the incidence of the *combined endpoint* of chest pain, myocardial infarction, or death.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] An example of a cancer study powered for a combined endpoint is disease-free survival; trial participants experiencing either death or discovery of any recurrence would constitute the endpoint.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Overall Treatment Utility is an example of a multidimensional composite endpoint in cancer clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Regarding humane endpoints, a combined endpoint may constitute a threshold where there is enough cumulative degree of disease, symptoms, signs or laboratory abnormalities to motivate an intervention.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The response rate is the percentage of patients on whom a therapy has some defined effect; for example, the cancer shrinks or disappears after treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] When used as a clinical endpoint for trials of cancer treatments, this is often called the *objective response rate* (ORR).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Each trial, for whatever illness or condition, may define what is considered a *complete response* (CR) or *partial response* (PR) to the therapy or intervention.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Hence the trials report the complete response rate and the *overall response rate* which includes CR and PR.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] Various studies on a particular topic often do not address the same outcomes, making it difficult to draw clinically useful conclusions when a group of studies is looked at as a whole.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-endpoint] The Core Outcomes in Women's Health (CROWN) Initiative is one effort to standardize outcomes.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Depending on product type and development stage, investigators initially enroll volunteers or patients into small pilot studies, and subsequently conduct progressively larger scale comparative studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials can vary in size and cost, and they can involve a single research center or multiple centers, in one country or in multiple countries.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical study design aims to ensure the scientific validity and reproducibility of the results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Costs for clinical trials can range into the billions of dollars per approved drug, and the complete trial process to approval may require 7–15 years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The sponsor may be a governmental organization or a pharmaceutical, biotechnology or medical-device company.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Certain functions necessary to the trial, such as monitoring and lab work, may be managed by an outsourced partner, such as a contract research organization or a central laboratory.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Only 10 percent of all drugs started in human clinical trials become approved drugs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Data collection is a key activity within clinical trials and digital data collection tools can assist greatly in this effort.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Some clinical trials involve healthy subjects with no pre-existing medical conditions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Other clinical trials pertain to people with specific health conditions who are willing to try an experimental treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Pilot experiments are conducted to gain insights for design of the clinical trial to follow.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] There are two goals to testing medical treatments: to learn whether they work well enough, called "efficacy", or "effectiveness"; and to learn whether they are safe enough, called "safety".
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Neither is an absolute criterion; both safety and efficacy are evaluated relative to how the treatment is intended to be used, what other treatments are available, and the severity of the disease or condition.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For example, many drugs to treat cancer have severe side effects that would not be acceptable for an over-the-counter pain medication, yet the cancer drugs have been approved since they are used under a physician's care and are used for a life-threatening condition.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In the US the elderly constitute 14% of the population, while they consume over one-third of drugs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] People over 55 (or a similar cutoff age) are often excluded from trials because their greater health issues and drug use complicate data interpretation, and because they have different physiological capacity than younger people.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Children and people with unrelated medical conditions are also frequently excluded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Pregnant women are often excluded due to potential risks to the fetus.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The sponsor designs the trial in coordination with a panel of expert clinical investigators, including what alternative or existing treatments to compare to the new drug and what type(s) of patients might benefit.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] If the sponsor cannot obtain enough test subjects at one location investigators at other locations are recruited to join the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] During the trial, investigators recruit subjects with the predetermined characteristics, administer the treatment(s) and collect data on the subjects' health for a defined time period.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Data include measurements such as vital signs, concentration of the study drug in the blood or tissues, changes to symptoms, and whether improvement or worsening of the condition targeted by the study drug occurs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The researchers send the data to the trial sponsor, who then analyzes the pooled data using statistical tests.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] While most clinical trials test one alternative to the novel intervention, some expand to three or four and may include a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Except for small, single-location trials, the design and objectives are specified in a document called a clinical trial protocol.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The protocol is the trial's "operating manual" and ensures all researchers perform the trial in the same way on similar subjects and that the data is comparable across all subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] As a trial is designed to test hypotheses and rigorously monitor and assess outcomes, it can be seen as an application of the scientific method, specifically the experimental step.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The most common clinical trials evaluate new pharmaceutical products, medical devices, biologics, diagnostic assays, psychological therapies, or other interventions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials may be required before a national regulatory authority approves marketing of the innovation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Similarly to drugs, manufacturers of medical devices in the United States are required to conduct clinical trials for premarket approval.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Device trials may compare a new device to an established therapy, or may compare similar devices to each other.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] An example of the former in the field of vascular surgery is the Open versus Endovascular Repair (OVER trial) for the treatment of abdominal aortic aneurysm, which compared the older open aortic repair technique to the newer endovascular aneurysm repair device.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] An example of the latter are clinical trials on mechanical devices used in the management of adult female urinary incontinence.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Similarly to drugs, medical or surgical procedures may be subjected to clinical trials, such as comparing different surgical approaches in treatment of fibroids for subfertility.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] However, when clinical trials are unethical or logistically impossible in the surgical setting, case-controlled studies will be replaced.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Besides being participants in a clinical trial, members of the public can be actively collaborate with researchers in designing and conducting clinical research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] This is known as patient and public involvement (PPI).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Public involvement involves a working partnership between patients, caregivers, people with lived experience, and researchers to shape and influence what is researched and how.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] PPI can improve the quality of research and make it more relevant and accessible.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] People with current or past experience of illness can provide a different perspective than professionals and compliment their knowledge.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Through their personal knowledge they can identify research topics that are relevant and important to those living with an illness or using a service.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] They can also help to make the research more grounded in the needs of the specific communities they are part of.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Public contributors can also ensure that the research is presented in plain language that is clear to the wider society and the specific groups it is most relevant for.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Although early medical experimentation was performed often, the use of a control group to provide an accurate comparison for the demonstration of the intervention's efficacy was generally lacking.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For instance, Lady Mary Wortley Montagu, who campaigned for the introduction of inoculation (then called variolation) to prevent smallpox, arranged for seven prisoners who had been sentenced to death to undergo variolation in exchange for their life.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Although they survived and did not contract smallpox, there was no control group to assess whether this result was due to the inoculation or some other factor.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Similar experiments performed by Edward Jenner over his smallpox vaccine were equally conceptually flawed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The first proper clinical trial was conducted by the Scottish physician James Lind.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The disease scurvy, now known to be caused by a Vitamin C deficiency, would often have terrible effects on the welfare of the crew of long-distance ocean voyages.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In 1740, the catastrophic result of Anson's circumnavigation attracted much attention in Europe; out of 1900 men, 1400 had died, most of them allegedly from having contracted scurvy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] John Woodall, an English military surgeon of the British East India Company, had recommended the consumption of citrus fruit from the 17th century, but their use did not become widespread.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Lind conducted the first systematic clinical trial in 1747.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] He included a dietary supplement of an acidic quality in the experiment after two months at sea, when the ship was already afflicted with scurvy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] He divided twelve scorbutic sailors into six groups of two.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The treatment of group five stopped after six days when they ran out of fruit, but by then one sailor was fit for duty while the other had almost recovered.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Apart from that, only group one also showed some effect of its treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Each year, May 20 is celebrated as Clinical Trials Day in honor of Lind's research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] After 1750 the discipline began to take its modern shape.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The English doctor John Haygarth demonstrated the importance of a control group for the correct identification of the placebo effect in his celebrated study of the ineffective remedy called *Perkin's tractors*.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] This was followed in 1843 by a proposal from Irish doctor James Henry for a controlled trial of cold-water therapy vs sulphur for scabies treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Further work on the placebo effect was carried out by the eminent physician Sir William Gull, 1st Baronet in the 1860s.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] 1884), who worked at Guy's Hospital in London, made substantial contributions to the process of clinical trials, where "he separated chronic nephritis with secondary hypertension from what we now term essential hypertension.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Fisher still play a role in clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] While working for the Rothamsted experimental station in the field of agriculture, Fisher developed his *Principles of experimental design* in the 1920s as an accurate methodology for the proper design of experiments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Of these, blocking and factorial design are seldom applied in clinical trials, because the experimental units are human subjects and there is typically only one independent intervention: the treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The British Medical Research Council officially recognized the importance of clinical trials from the 1930s.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The council established the *Therapeutic Trials Committee* to advise and assist in the arrangement of properly controlled clinical trials on new products that seem likely on experimental grounds to have value in the treatment of disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The first randomised curative trial was carried out at the MRC Tuberculosis Research Unit by Sir Geoffrey Marshall (1887–1982).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The trial, carried out between 1946 and 1947, aimed to test the efficacy of the chemical streptomycin for curing pulmonary tuberculosis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The trial was both double-blind and placebo-controlled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The methodology of clinical trials was further developed by Sir Austin Bradford Hill, who had been involved in the streptomycin trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] From the 1920s, Hill applied statistics to medicine, attending the lectures of renowned mathematician Karl Pearson, among others.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] He became famous for a landmark study carried out in collaboration with Richard Doll on the correlation between smoking and lung cancer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] International clinical trials day is celebrated on 20 May.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The acronyms used in the titling of clinical trials are often contrived, and have been the subject of derision.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials are classified by the research objective created by the investigators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials are conducted typically in four phases, with each phase using different numbers of subjects and having a different purpose to construct focus on identifying a specific effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials involving new drugs are commonly classified into five phases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Each phase of the drug approval process is treated as a separate clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The drug development process will normally proceed through phases I–IV over many years, frequently involving a decade or longer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] If the drug successfully passes through phases I, II, and III, it will usually be approved by the national regulatory authority for use in the general population.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Phase IV trials are performed after the newly approved drug, diagnostic or device is marketed, providing assessment about risks, benefits, or best uses.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A fundamental distinction in evidence-based practice is between observational studies and randomized controlled trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Types of observational studies in epidemiology, such as the cohort study and the case-control study, provide less compelling evidence than the randomized controlled trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In observational studies, the investigators retrospectively assess associations between the treatments given to participants and their health status, with potential for considerable errors in design and interpretation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A randomized controlled trial can provide compelling evidence that the study treatment causes an effect on human health.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Some phase II and most phase III drug trials are designed as randomized, double-blind, and placebo-controlled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical studies having small numbers of subjects may be "sponsored" by single researchers or a small group of researchers, and are designed to test simple questions or feasibility to expand the research for a more comprehensive randomized controlled trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical studies can be "sponsored" (financed and organized) by academic institutions, pharmaceutical companies, government entities and even private groups.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Trials are conducted for new drugs, biotechnology, diagnostic assays or medical devices to determine their safety and efficacy prior to being submitted for regulatory review that would determine market approval.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In cases where giving a placebo to a person suffering from a disease may be unethical, "active comparator" (also known as "active control") trials may be conducted instead.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In trials with an active control group, subjects are given either the experimental treatment or a previously approved treatment with known effectiveness.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In other cases, sponsors may conduct an active comparator trial to establish an efficacy claim relative to the active comparator instead of the placebo in labeling.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A master protocol includes multiple substudies, which may have different objectives and involve coordinated efforts to evaluate one or more medical products in one or more diseases or conditions within the overall study structure.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Trials that could develop a master protocol include the umbrella trial (multiple medical products for a single disease), platform trial (multiple products for a single disease entering and leaving the platform), and basket trial (one medical product for multiple diseases or disease subtypes).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Genetic testing enables researchers to group patients according to their genetic profile, deliver drugs based on that profile to that group and compare the results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Multiple companies can participate, each bringing a different drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The first such approach targets squamous cell cancer, which includes varying genetic disruptions from patient to patient.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Amgen, AstraZeneca and Pfizer are involved, the first time they have worked together in a late-stage trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Patients whose genomic profiles do not match any of the trial drugs receive a drug designed to stimulate the immune system to attack cancer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A clinical trial protocol is a document used to define and manage the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] All study investigators are expected to strictly observe the protocol.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The protocol describes the scientific rationale, objective(s), design, methodology, statistical considerations and organization of the planned trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Details of the trial are provided in documents referenced in the protocol, such as an investigator's brochure.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The protocol contains a precise study plan to assure safety and health of the trial subjects and to provide an exact template for trial conduct by investigators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] This allows data to be combined across all investigators/sites.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The protocol also informs the study administrators (often a contract research organization).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The format and content of clinical trial protocols sponsored by pharmaceutical, biotechnology or medical device companies in the United States, European Union, or Japan have been standardized to follow Good Clinical Practice guidance issued by the International Conference on Harmonisation (ICH).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Regulatory authorities in Canada, China, South Korea, and the UK also follow ICH guidelines.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Journals such as *Trials*, encourage investigators to publish their protocols.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials recruit study subjects to sign a document representing their "informed consent".
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The document includes details such as its purpose, duration, required procedures, risks, potential benefits, key contacts and institutional requirements.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The participant then decides whether to sign the document.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The document is not a contract, as the participant can withdraw at any time without penalty.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Informed consent is a legal process in which a recruit is instructed about key facts before deciding whether to participate.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Researchers explain the details of the study in terms the subject can understand.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The information is presented in the subject's native language.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Generally, children cannot autonomously provide informed consent, but depending on their age and other factors, may be required to provide informed assent.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In any clinical trial, the number of subjects, also called the sample size, has a large impact on the ability to reliably detect and measure the effects of the intervention.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] This ability is described as its "power", which must be calculated before initiating a study to figure out if the study is worth its costs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In general, a larger sample size increases the statistical power, also the cost.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The statistical power estimates the ability of a trial to detect a difference of a particular size (or larger) between the treatment and control groups.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For example, a trial of a lipid-lowering drug versus placebo with 100 patients in each group might have a power of 0.90 to detect a difference between placebo and trial groups receiving dosage of 10 mg/dL or more, but only 0.70 to detect a difference of 6 mg/dL.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Merely giving a treatment can have nonspecific effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] These are controlled for by the inclusion of patients who receive only a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Subjects are assigned randomly without informing them to which group they belonged.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Many trials are doubled-blinded so that researchers do not know to which group a subject is assigned.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Assigning a subject to a placebo group can pose an ethical problem if it violates his or her right to receive the best available treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The Declaration of Helsinki provides guidelines on this issue.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials are only a small part of the research that goes into developing a new treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Potential drugs, for example, first have to be discovered, purified, characterized, and tested in labs (in cell and animal studies) before ever undergoing clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In all, about 1,000 potential drugs are tested before just one reaches the point of being tested in a clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For example, a new cancer drug has, on average, six years of research behind it before it even makes it to clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] But the major holdup in making new cancer drugs available is the time it takes to complete clinical trials themselves.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] On average, about eight years pass from the time a cancer drug enters clinical trials until it receives approval from regulatory agencies for sale to the public.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Drugs for other diseases have similar timelines.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A clinical trial might also include an extended post-study follow-up period from months to years for people who have participated in the trial, a so-called "extension phase", which aims to identify long-term impact of the treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The biggest barrier to completing studies is the shortage of people who take part.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] All drug and many device trials target a subset of the population, meaning not everyone can participate.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Some drug trials require patients to have unusual combinations of disease characteristics.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] It is a challenge to find the appropriate patients and obtain their consent, especially when they may receive no direct benefit (because they are not paid, the study drug is not yet proven to work, or the patient may receive a placebo).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In the case of cancer patients, fewer than 5% of adults with cancer will participate in drug trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] According to the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America (PhRMA), about 400 cancer medicines were being tested in clinical trials in 2005.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Not all of these will prove to be useful, but those that are may be delayed in getting approved because the number of participants is so low.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For clinical trials involving potential for seasonal influences (such as airborne allergies, seasonal affective disorder, influenza, and skin diseases), the study may be done during a limited part of the year (such as spring for pollen allergies), when the drug can be tested.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials that do not involve a new drug usually have a much shorter duration.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] (Exceptions are epidemiological studies, such as the Nurses' Health Study).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials designed by a local investigator, and (in the US) federally funded clinical trials, are almost always administered by the researcher who designed the study and applied for the grant.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Small-scale device studies may be administered by the sponsoring company.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials of new drugs are usually administered by a contract research organization (CRO) hired by the sponsoring company.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The sponsor provides the drug and medical oversight.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A CRO is contracted to perform all the administrative work on a clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For phases II–IV the CRO recruits participating researchers, trains them, provides them with supplies, coordinates study administration and data collection, sets up meetings, monitors the sites for compliance with the clinical protocol, and ensures the sponsor receives data from every site.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Specialist site management organizations can also be hired to coordinate with the CRO to ensure rapid IRB/IEC approval and faster site initiation and patient recruitment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Phase I clinical trials of new medicines are often conducted in a specialist clinical trial clinic, with dedicated pharmacologists, where the subjects can be observed by full-time staff.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] These clinics are often run by a CRO which specialises in these studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] At a participating site, one or more research assistants (often nurses) do most of the work in conducting the clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In the context of a clinical trial, quality typically refers to the absence of errors which can impact decision making, both during the conduct of the trial and in use of the trial results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] An Interactional Justice Model may be used to test the effects of willingness to talk with a doctor about clinical trial enrollment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Results found that potential clinical trial candidates were less likely to enroll in clinical trials if the patient is more willing to talk with their doctor.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The reasoning behind this discovery may be patients are happy with their current care.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Another reason for the negative relationship between perceived fairness and clinical trial enrollment is the lack of independence from the care provider.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Results found that there is a positive relationship between a lack of willingness to talk with their doctor and clinical trial enrollment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Lack of willingness to talk about clinical trials with current care providers may be due to patients' independence from the doctor.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Patients who are less likely to talk about clinical trials are more willing to use other sources of information to gain a better insight of alternative treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trial enrollment should be motivated to utilize websites and television advertising to inform the public about clinical trial enrollment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The last decade has seen a proliferation of information technology use in the planning and conduct of clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trial management systems are often used by research sponsors or CROs to help plan and manage the operational aspects of a clinical trial, particularly with respect to investigational sites.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Advanced analytics for identifying researchers and research sites with expertise in a given area utilize public and private information about ongoing research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Web-based electronic data capture (EDC) and clinical data management systems are used in a majority of clinical trials to collect case report data from sites, manage its quality and prepare it for analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Interactive voice response systems are used by sites to register the enrollment of patients using a phone and to allocate patients to a particular treatment arm (although phones are being increasingly replaced with web-based (IWRS) tools which are sometimes part of the EDC system).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] While patient-reported outcome were often paper based in the past, measurements are increasingly being collected using web portals or hand-held ePRO (or eDiary) devices, sometimes wireless.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Statistical software is used to analyze the collected data and prepare them for regulatory submission.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Access to many of these applications are increasingly aggregated in web-based clinical trial portals.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In 2011, the FDA approved a phase I trial that used telemonitoring, also known as remote patient monitoring, to collect biometric data in patients' homes and transmit it electronically to the trial database.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] This technology provides many more data points and is far more convenient for patients, because they have fewer visits to trial sites.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] As noted below, decentralized clinical trials are those that do not require patients' physical presence at a site, and instead rely largely on digital health data collection, digital informed consent processes, and so on.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The guidance calls for clearly defining the research question of a trial by specifying its estimand.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] An estimand is a clear description of the treatment effect a trial aims to quantify.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The guidance provides a structured framework for defining estimands, which consists of five attributes: (i) population of patients; (ii) treatment conditions being compared; (iii) the endpoint; (iv) the summary measure; and (v) how intercurrent events are handled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Tutorials on how to implement the estimand framework is available.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] A clinical trial produces data that could reveal quantitative differences between two or more interventions; statistical analyses are used to determine whether such differences are true, result from chance, or are the same as no treatment (placebo).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Data from a clinical trial accumulate gradually over the trial duration, extending from months to years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Accordingly, results for participants recruited early in the study become available for analysis while subjects are still being assigned to treatment groups in the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Early analysis may allow the emerging evidence to assist decisions about whether to stop the study, or to reassign participants to the more successful segment of the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Investigators may also want to stop a trial when data analysis shows no treatment effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Clinical trials are closely supervised by appropriate regulatory authorities.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] All studies involving a medical or therapeutic intervention on patients must be approved by a supervising ethics committee before permission is granted to run the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The local ethics committee has discretion on how it will supervise noninterventional studies (observational studies or those using already collected data).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In the US, this body is called the Institutional Review Board (IRB); in the EU, they are called Ethics committees.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Most IRBs are located at the local investigator's hospital or institution, but some sponsors allow the use of a central (independent/for profit) IRB for investigators who work at smaller institutions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] To be ethical, researchers must obtain the full and informed consent of participating human subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] (One of the IRB's main functions is to ensure potential patients are adequately informed about the clinical trial.) If the patient is unable to consent for him/herself, researchers can seek consent from the patient's legally authorized representative.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In addition, the clinical trial participants must be made aware that they can withdraw from the clinical trial at any time without any adverse action taken against them.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In California, the state has prioritized the individuals who can serve as the legally authorized representative.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In some US locations, the local IRB must certify researchers and their staff before they can conduct clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] They must understand the federal patient privacy (HIPAA) law and good clinical practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The International Conference of Harmonisation Guidelines for Good Clinical Practice is a set of standards used internationally for the conduct of clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The guidelines aim to ensure the "rights, safety and well being of trial subjects are protected".
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The notion of informed consent of participating human subjects exists in many countries but its precise definition may still vary.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Informed consent is clearly a 'necessary' condition for ethical conduct but does not 'ensure' ethical conduct.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In compassionate use trials the latter becomes a particularly difficult problem.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The final objective is to serve the community of patients or future patients in a best-possible and most responsible way.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] However, it may be hard to turn this objective into a well-defined, quantified, objective function.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In some cases this can be done, however, for instance, for questions of when to stop sequential treatments (see Odds algorithm), and then quantified methods may play an important role.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Additional ethical concerns are present when conducting clinical trials on children (pediatrics), and in emergency or epidemic situations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Ethically balancing the rights of multiple stakeholders may be difficult.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For example, when drug trials fail, the sponsors may have a duty to tell current and potential investors immediately, which means both the research staff and the enrolled participants may first hear about the end of a trial through public business news.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The US Congress signed into law a bill which requires phase II and phase III clinical trials to be registered by the sponsor on the clinicaltrials.gov website compiled by the National Institutes of Health.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Drug researchers not directly employed by pharmaceutical companies often seek grants from manufacturers, and manufacturers often look to academic researchers to conduct studies within networks of universities and their hospitals, e.g., for translational cancer research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Similarly, competition for tenured academic positions, government grants and prestige create conflicts of interest among academic scientists.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] According to one study, approximately 75% of articles retracted for misconduct-related reasons have no declared industry financial support.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Seeding trials are particularly controversial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In the United States, all clinical trials submitted to the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) as part of a drug approval process are independently assessed by clinical experts within the FDA, including inspections of primary data collection at selected clinical trial sites.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In 2001, the editors of 12 major journals issued a joint editorial, published in each journal, on the control over clinical trials exerted by sponsors, particularly targeting the use of contracts which allow sponsors to review the studies prior to publication and withhold publication.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] They strengthened editorial restrictions to counter the effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] The editorial noted that contract research organizations had, by 2000, received 60% of the grants from pharmaceutical companies in the US.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Researchers may be restricted from contributing to the trial design, accessing the raw data, and interpreting the results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Issues referred for attention in this respect include potential observation bias, duration of the observation time for maintenance studies, the selection of the patient populations, factors that affect placebo response, and funding sources.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Conducting clinical trials of vaccines during epidemics and pandemics is subject to ethical concerns.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] For diseases with high mortality rates like Ebola, assigning individuals to a placebo or control group can be viewed as a death sentence.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In response to ethical concerns regarding clinical research during epidemics, the National Academy of Medicine authored a report identifying seven ethical and scientific considerations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Pregnant women and children are typically excluded from clinical trials as vulnerable populations, though the data to support excluding them is not robust.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] By excluding them from clinical trials, information about the safety and effectiveness of therapies for these populations is often lacking.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] During the early history of the HIV/AIDS epidemic, a scientist noted that by excluding these groups from potentially life-saving treatment, they were being "protected to death".
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Projects such as Research Ethics for Vaccines, Epidemics, and New Technologies (PREVENT) have advocated for the ethical inclusion of pregnant women in vaccine trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Inclusion of children in clinical trials has additional moral considerations, as children lack decision-making autonomy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] Trials in the past had been criticized for using hospitalized children or orphans; these ethical concerns effectively stopped future research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] In efforts to maintain effective pediatric care, several European countries and the US have policies to entice or compel pharmaceutical companies to conduct pediatric trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p01] International guidance recommends ethical pediatric trials by limiting harm, considering varied risks, and taking into account the complexities of pediatric care.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] A systematic concurrent safety review is frequently employed to assure research participant safety.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The conduct and on-going review is designed to be proportional to the risk of the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Typically this role is filled by a Data and Safety Committee, an externally appointed Medical Safety Monitor, an Independent Safety Officer, or for small or low-risk studies the principal investigator.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] For safety reasons, many clinical trials of drugs are designed to exclude women of childbearing age, pregnant women, or women who become pregnant during the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In some cases, the male partners of these women are also excluded or required to take birth control measures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] This allows the local investigators to make an informed judgment on whether to participate in the study or not.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The sponsor is also responsible for monitoring the results of the study as they come in from the various sites as the trial proceeds.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In larger clinical trials, a sponsor will use the services of a data monitoring committee (DMC, known in the US as a data safety monitoring board).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] This independent group of clinicians and statisticians meets periodically to review the unblinded data the sponsor has received so far.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The DMC has the power to recommend termination of the study based on their review, for example if the study treatment is causing more deaths than the standard treatment, or seems to be causing unexpected and study-related serious adverse events.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The sponsor is responsible for collecting adverse event reports from all site investigators in the study, and for informing all the investigators of the sponsor's judgment as to whether these adverse events were related or not related to the study treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] FDA regulations state that participating in clinical trials is voluntary, with the subject having the right not to participate or to end participation at any time.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The ethical principle of *primum non-nocere* ("first, do no harm") guides the trial, and if an investigator believes the study treatment may be harming subjects in the study, the investigator can stop participating at any time.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] On the other hand, investigators often have a financial interest in recruiting subjects, and could act unethically to obtain and maintain their participation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The local investigators are responsible for conducting the study according to the study protocol, and supervising the study staff throughout the duration of the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The local investigator or his/her study staff are also responsible for ensuring the potential subjects in the study understand the risks and potential benefits of participating in the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In other words, they (or their legally authorized representatives) must give truly informed consent.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Local investigators are responsible for reviewing all adverse event reports sent by the sponsor.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] These adverse event reports contain the opinions of both the investigator (at the site where the adverse event occurred) and the sponsor, regarding the relationship of the adverse event to the study treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Local investigators also are responsible for making an independent judgment of these reports, and promptly informing the local IRB of all serious and study treatment-related adverse events.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] When a local investigator is the sponsor, there may not be formal adverse event reports, but study staff at all locations are responsible for informing the coordinating investigator of anything unexpected.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The local investigator is responsible for being truthful to the local IRB in all communications relating to the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Approval by an Institutional Review Board (IRB), or Independent Ethics Committee (IEC), is necessary before all but the most informal research can begin.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In commercial clinical trials, the study protocol is not approved by an IRB before the sponsor recruits sites to conduct the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] However, the study protocol and procedures have been tailored to fit generic IRB submission requirements.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In this case, and where there is no independent sponsor, each local site investigator submits the study protocol, the consent(s), the data collection forms, and supporting documentation to the local IRB.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Universities and most hospitals have in-house IRBs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Other researchers (such as in walk-in clinics) use independent IRBs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The IRB scrutinizes the study both for medical safety and for protection of the patients involved in the study, before it allows the researcher to begin the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] It may require changes in study procedures or in the explanations given to the patient.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] A required yearly "continuing review" report from the investigator updates the IRB on the progress of the study and any new safety information related to the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In the US, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) can audit the files of local site investigators after they have finished participating in a study, to see if they were correctly following study procedures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] This audit may be random, or for cause (because the investigator is suspected of fraudulent data).
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Avoiding an audit is an incentive for investigators to follow study procedures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] A 'covered clinical study' refers to a trial submitted to the FDA as part of a marketing application (for example, as part of an NDA or 510(k)), about which the FDA may require disclosure of financial interest of the clinical investigator in the outcome of the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] For example, the applicant must disclose whether an investigator owns equity in the sponsor, or owns proprietary interest in the product under investigation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Alternatively, many American pharmaceutical companies have moved some clinical trials overseas.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Benefits of conducting trials abroad include lower costs (in some countries) and the ability to run larger trials in shorter timeframes, whereas a potential disadvantage exists in lower-quality trial management.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Different countries have different regulatory requirements and enforcement abilities.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] An estimated 40% of all clinical trials now take place in Asia, Eastern Europe, and Central and South America.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] "There is no compulsory registration system for clinical trials in these countries and many do not follow European directives in their operations", says Jacob Sijtsma of the Netherlands-based WEMOS, an advocacy health organisation tracking clinical trials in developing countries.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Beginning in the 1980s, harmonization of clinical trial protocols was shown as feasible across countries of the European Union.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Aggregating safety data across clinical trials during drug development is important because trials are generally designed to focus on determining how well the drug works.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The safety data collected and aggregated across multiple trials as the drug is developed allows the sponsor, investigators and regulatory agencies to monitor the aggregate safety profile of experimental medicines as they are developed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The value of assessing aggregate safety data is: a) decisions based on aggregate safety assessment during development of the medicine can be made throughout the medicine's development and b) it sets up the sponsor and regulators well for assessing the medicine's safety after the drug is approved.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Clinical trial costs vary depending on trial phase, type of trial, and disease studied.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] A study of clinical trials conducted in the United States from 2004 to 2012 found the average cost of phase I trials to be between $1.4 million and $6.6 million, depending on the type of disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Phase II trials ranged from $7 million to $20 million, and phase III trials from $11 million to $53 million.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The cost of a study depends on many factors, especially the number of sites conducting the study, the number of patients involved, and whether the study treatment is already approved for medical use.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] These expenses are incurred over several years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In the US, sponsors may receive a 50 percent tax credit for clinical trials conducted on drugs being developed for the treatment of orphan diseases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] National health agencies, such as the US National Institutes of Health, offer grants to investigators who design clinical trials that attempt to answer research questions of interest to the agency.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In these cases, the investigator who writes the grant and administers the study acts as the sponsor, and coordinates data collection from any other sites.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] These other sites may or may not be paid for participating in the study, depending on the amount of the grant and the amount of effort expected from them.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Using internet resources can, in some cases, reduce the economic burden.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Investigators are often compensated for their work in clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Participants in phase I drug trials do not gain any direct health benefit from taking part.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] They are generally paid a fee for their time, with payments regulated and not related to any risk involved.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Motivations of healthy volunteers is not limited to financial reward and may include other motivations such as contributing to science and others.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] In later phase trials, subjects may not be paid to ensure their motivation for participating with potential for a health benefit or contributing to medical knowledge.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Small payments may be made for study-related expenses such as travel or as compensation for their time in providing follow-up information about their health after the trial treatment ends.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Phase 0 and phase I drug trials seek healthy volunteers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Most other clinical trials seek patients who have a specific disease or medical condition.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The diversity observed in society should be reflected in clinical trials through the appropriate inclusion of ethnic minority populations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Patient recruitment or participant recruitment plays a significant role in the activities and responsibilities of sites conducting clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] All volunteers being considered for a trial are required to undertake a medical screening.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] It has been observed that participants in clinical trials are disproportionately white.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Often, minorities are not informed about clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] One recent systematic review of the literature found that race/ethnicity as well as sex were not well-represented nor at times even tracked as participants in a large number of clinical trials of hearing loss management in adults.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] This may reduce the validity of findings in respect of non-white patients by not adequately representing the larger populations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Depending on the kind of participants required, sponsors of clinical trials, or contract research organizations working on their behalf, try to find sites with qualified personnel as well as access to people who could participate in the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Working with those sites, they may use various recruitment strategies, including patient databases, newspaper and radio advertisements, flyers, posters in places the patients might go (such as doctor's offices), and personal recruitment of trial participants by investigators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Volunteers may search directly to locate trials using a registry run by the U.S.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] National Institutes of Health and National Library of Medicine to identify studies that are currently recruiting participants, offering simplified navigation and real-time enrollment trial information.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Software exists to enable clinicians to find trial options for a possible participant based on genomic data for people with cancer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] The risk information seeking and processing (RISP) model analyzes social implications that affect attitudes and decision making pertaining to clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] People who hold a higher stake or interest in the treatment provided in a clinical trial showed a greater likelihood of seeking information about clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Cancer patients reported more optimistic attitudes towards clinical trials than the general population.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Having a more optimistic outlook on clinical trials also leads to greater likelihood of enrolling.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Matching involves a systematic comparison of a patient's clinical and demographic information against the eligibility criteria of various trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] Although trials are commonly conducted at major medical centers, some participants are excluded due to the distance and expenses required for travel, leading to hardship, disadvantage, and inequity for participants, especially those in rural and underserved communities.
[src:clinical-trials-design/clinical-trial-p02] "Decentralized clinical trials" minimize or eliminates the need for patients to travel to sites, and are now more widespread; a capability improved by telehealth and wearable technologies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] In medicine, an **intention-to-treat** (**ITT**) **analysis** of the results of a randomized controlled trial is based on the initial treatment assignment and not on the treatment eventually received.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] ITT analysis is intended to avoid various misleading artifacts that can arise in intervention research such as non-random attrition of participants from the study or crossover.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] ITT is also simpler than other forms of study design and analysis, because it does not require observation of compliance status for units assigned to different treatments or incorporation of compliance into the analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Although ITT analysis is widely employed in published clinical trials, it can be incorrectly described and there are some issues with its application.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Furthermore, there is no consensus on how to carry out an ITT analysis in the presence of missing outcome data.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Randomized clinical trials analyzed by the intention-to-treat (ITT) approach provide unbiased comparisons among the treatment groups.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Intention to treat analyses are done to avoid the effects of crossover and dropout, which may break the random assignment to the treatment groups in a study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] ITT analysis provides information about the potential effects of treatment policy rather than on the potential effects of specific treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Since it started in the 1960s, the principle of ITT has become widely accepted for the analysis of controlled clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] In an ITT population, none of the patients are excluded and the patients are analyzed according to the randomization scheme.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] In other words, for the purposes of ITT analysis, everyone who is randomized in the trial is considered to be part of the trial regardless of whether he or she is dosed or completes the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Medical investigators often have difficulties in completing ITT analysis because of clinical trial issues like missing data or poor treatment protocol adherence.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] To address some of these issues, many clinical trials have excluded participants after the random assignment in their analysis, which is often referred to as *modified intention-to-treat analysis* or mITT.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Trials employing mITT have been linked to industry sponsorship and conflicts of interest by the authors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] An important problem is the occurrence of missing data for participants in a clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] This can happen when patients are lost to follow-up (for instance, by withdrawal due to adverse effects of the intervention) and no response is obtainable for these patients.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] However, full application of ITT analysis can only be performed where there is complete outcome data for all randomized subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] In order to include such participants in an analysis, outcome data could be imputed which involves making assumptions about the outcomes in the lost participants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Another approach would be *efficacy subset analysis* which selects the subset of the patients who received the treatment of interest—regardless of initial randomization—and who have not dropped out for any reason.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] This approach can introduce biases to the statistical analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] It can also inflate the chance of a false positive; this effect is greater the larger the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] ITT analysis requires participants to be included even if they did not fully adhere to the protocol.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] Participants who strayed from the protocol (for instance, by not adhering to the prescribed intervention, or by being withdrawn from active treatment) should still be kept in the analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] An extreme variation of this is the participants who receive the treatment from the group they were not allocated to, who should be kept in their original group for the analysis.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] This issue causes no problems provided that the systematic reviewer can extract the appropriate data from the trial reports.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] The rationale for this approach is that, in the first instance, the goal is to estimate the effects of allocating an intervention in practice, not the effects in the subgroup of the participants who adhere to it.
[src:clinical-trials-design/intention-to-treat-analysis] In comparison, in a per-protocol analysis, only patients who complete the entire clinical trial according to the protocol are counted towards the final results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The **phases of clinical research** are the stages in which scientists conduct experiments with a health intervention to obtain sufficient evidence for a process considered effective as a medical treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] For drug development, the clinical phases start with testing for drug safety in a few human subjects, then expand to many study participants (potentially tens of thousands) to determine if the treatment is effective.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Clinical research is conducted on drug candidates, vaccine candidates, new medical devices, and new diagnostic assays.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Clinical trials testing potential medical products are commonly classified into four phases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The drug development process will normally proceed through all four phases over many years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] When expressed specifically, a clinical trial phase is capitalized both in name and Roman numeral, such as "Phase I" clinical trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase IV trials are 'post-marketing' or 'surveillance' studies conducted to monitor safety over several years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Before clinical trials are undertaken for a candidate drug, vaccine, medical device, or diagnostic assay, the product candidate is tested extensively in preclinical studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Such studies involve *in vitro* (test tube or cell culture) and *in vivo* (animal model) experiments using wide-ranging doses of the study agent to obtain preliminary efficacy, toxicity and pharmacokinetic information.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Such tests assist the developer to decide whether a drug candidate has scientific merit for further development as an investigational new drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase 0 is a designation for optional exploratory trials, originally introduced by the United States Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) 2006 Guidance on Exploratory Investigational New Drug (IND) Studies, but now generally adopted as standard practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase 0 trials are also known as human microdosing studies and are designed to speed up the development of promising drugs or imaging agents by establishing very early on whether the drug or agent behaves in human subjects as was expected from preclinical studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Distinctive features of Phase 0 trials include the administration of single subtherapeutic doses of the study drug to a small number of subjects (10 to 15) to gather preliminary data on the agent's pharmacokinetics (what the body does to the drugs).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A Phase 0 study gives no data on safety or efficacy, being by definition a dose too low to cause any therapeutic effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Drug development companies carry out Phase 0 studies to rank drug candidates to decide which has the best pharmacokinetic parameters in humans to take forward into further development.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] They enable go/no-go decisions to be based on relevant human models instead of relying on sometimes inconsistent animal data.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase I trials were formerly referred to as "first-in-man studies" but the field generally moved to the gender-neutral language phrase "first-in-humans" in the 1990s; these trials are the first stage of testing in human subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] They are designed to test the safety, side effects, best dose, and formulation method for the drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase I trials are not randomized, and thus are vulnerable to selection bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Normally, a small group of 20–100 healthy volunteers will be recruited.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] These trials are often conducted in a clinical trial clinic, where the subject can be observed by full-time staff.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] These clinical trial clinics are often run by contract research organization (CROs) who conduct these studies on behalf of pharmaceutical companies or other research investigators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The subject who receives the drug is usually observed until several half-lives of the drug have passed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This phase is designed to assess the safety (pharmacovigilance), tolerability, pharmacokinetics, and pharmacodynamics of a drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase I trials normally include dose-ranging, also called dose escalation studies, so that the best and safest dose can be found and to discover the point at which a compound is too poisonous to administer.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The tested range of doses will usually be a fraction of the dose that caused harm in animal testing.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase I trials most often include healthy volunteers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] However, there are some circumstances when clinical patients are used, such as patients who have terminal cancer or HIV and the treatment is likely to make healthy individuals ill.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] These studies are usually conducted in tightly controlled clinics called Central Pharmacological Units, where participants receive 24-hour medical attention and oversight.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In addition to the previously mentioned unhealthy individuals, "patients who have typically already tried and failed to improve on the existing standard therapies" may also participate in Phase I trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Volunteers are paid a variable inconvenience fee for their time spent in the volunteer center.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Before beginning a Phase I trial, the sponsor must submit an Investigational New Drug application to the FDA detailing the preliminary data on the drug gathered from cellular models and animal studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Single ascending dose (Phase Ia): In single ascending dose studies, small groups of subjects are given a single dose of the drug while they are observed and tested for a period of time to confirm safety.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Typically, a small number of participants, usually three, are entered sequentially at a particular dose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If they do not exhibit any adverse side effects, and the pharmacokinetic data are roughly in line with predicted safe values, the dose is escalated, and a new group of subjects is then given a higher dose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If unacceptable toxicity is observed in any of the three participants, an additional number of participants, usually three, are treated at the same dose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This is continued until pre-calculated pharmacokinetic safety levels are reached, or intolerable side effects start showing up (at which point the drug is said to have reached the maximum tolerated dose (MTD)).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If an additional unacceptable toxicity is observed, then the dose escalation is terminated and that dose, or perhaps the previous dose, is declared to be the maximally tolerated dose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This particular design assumes that the maximally tolerated dose occurs when approximately one-third of the participants experience unacceptable toxicity.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Variations of this design exist, but most are similar.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Multiple ascending dose (Phase Ib): Multiple ascending dose studies investigate the pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of multiple doses of the drug, looking at safety and tolerability.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In these studies, a group of patients receives multiple low doses of the drug, while samples (of blood, and other fluids) are collected at various time points and analyzed to acquire information on how the drug is processed within the body.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The dose is subsequently escalated for further groups, up to a predetermined level.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A short trial designed to investigate any differences in absorption of the drug by the body, caused by eating before the drug is given.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] These studies are usually run as a crossover study, with volunteers being given two identical doses of the drug while fasted, and after being fed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Once a dose or range of doses is determined, the next goal is to evaluate whether the drug has any biological activity or effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase II trials are performed on larger groups (50–300 individuals) and are designed to assess how well the drug works, as well as to continue Phase I safety assessments in a larger group of volunteers and patients.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Genetic testing is common, particularly when there is evidence of variation in metabolic rate.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] When the development process for a new drug fails, this usually occurs during Phase II trials when the drug is discovered not to work as planned, or to have toxic effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase II studies are sometimes divided into Phase IIa and Phase IIb.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Some Phase II trials are designed as case series, demonstrating a drug's safety and activity in a selected group of participants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Other Phase II trials are designed as randomized controlled trials, where some patients receive the drug/device and others receive placebo/standard treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Randomized Phase II trials have far fewer patients than randomized Phase III trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In the first stage, the investigator attempts to rule out drugs that have no or little biologic activity.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] For example, the researcher may specify that a drug must have some minimal level of activity, say, in 20% of participants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If the estimated activity level is less than 20%, the researcher chooses not to consider this drug further, at least not at that maximally tolerated dose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If the estimated activity level exceeds 20%, the researcher will add more participants to get a better estimate of the response rate.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A typical study for ruling out a 20% or lower response rate enters 14 participants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] If no response is observed in the first 14 participants, the drug is considered not likely to have a 20% or higher activity level.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The number of additional participants added depends on the degree of precision desired, but ranges from 10 to 20.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Thus, a typical cancer phase II study might include fewer than 30 people to estimate the response rate.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] When a study assesses efficacy, it is looking at whether the drug given in the specific manner described in the study is able to influence an outcome of interest (e.g. tumor size) in the chosen population (e.g. cancer patients with no other ongoing diseases).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] When a study is assessing effectiveness, it is determining whether a treatment will influence the disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In an effectiveness study, it is essential that participants are treated as they would be when the treatment is prescribed in actual practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] That would mean that there should be no aspects of the study designed to increase compliance above those that would occur in routine clinical practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The outcomes in effectiveness studies are also more generally applicable than in most efficacy studies (for example does the patient feel better, come to the hospital less or live longer in effectiveness studies as opposed to better test scores or lower cell counts in efficacy studies).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] There is usually less rigid control of the type of participant to be included in effectiveness studies than in efficacy studies, as the researchers are interested in whether the drug will have a broad effect in the population of patients with the disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase I trials historically have experienced the lowest success, having about a 66% failure rate due mainly to adverse effects and other toxicity concerns.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A 2022 review found that about 90% of drug candidates fail over the course of Phases I-III, mainly due to absence of therapeutic efficacy, toxicity, non-specific drug properties, poor strategic planning, and recognition that the compound will not succeed commercially.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This phase is designed to assess the effectiveness of the new intervention and, thereby, its value in clinical practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase III studies are randomized controlled multicenter trials on large patient groups (300–3,000 or more depending upon the disease/medical condition studied) and are aimed at being the definitive assessment of how effective the drug is, in comparison with current 'gold standard' treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Because of their size and comparatively long duration, Phase III trials are the most expensive, time-consuming and difficult trials to design and run, especially in therapies for chronic medical conditions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase III trials of chronic conditions or diseases often have a short follow-up period for evaluation, relative to the period of time the intervention might be used in practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] It is common practice that certain Phase III trials will continue while the regulatory submission is pending at the appropriate regulatory agency.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This allows patients to continue to receive possibly lifesaving drugs until the drug can be obtained by purchase.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] While not required in all cases, it is typically expected that there be at least two successful Phase III trials, demonstrating a drug's safety and efficacy, to obtain approval from the appropriate regulatory agencies such as FDA (US), or the EMA (European Union).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Once a drug has proved satisfactory after Phase III trials, the trial results are usually combined into a large document containing a comprehensive description of the methods and results of human and animal studies, manufacturing procedures, formulation details, and shelf life.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] This collection of information makes up the "regulatory submission" that is provided for review to the appropriate regulatory authorities in different countries.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] They will review the submission, and if it is acceptable, give the sponsor approval to market the drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Most drugs undergoing Phase III clinical trials can be marketed under FDA norms with proper recommendations and guidelines through a New Drug Application (NDA) containing all manufacturing, preclinical, and clinical data.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In case of any adverse effects being reported anywhere, the drugs need to be recalled immediately from the market.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] While most pharmaceutical companies refrain from this practice, it is not abnormal to see many drugs undergoing Phase III clinical trials in the market.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The design of individual trials may be altered during a trial – usually during Phase II or III – to accommodate interim results for the benefit of the treatment, adjust statistical analysis, or to reach early termination of an unsuccessful design, a process called an "adaptive design".
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Adaptive designs within ongoing Phase II–III clinical trials on candidate therapeutics may shorten trial durations and use fewer subjects, possibly expediting decisions for early termination or success, and coordinating design changes for a specific trial across its international locations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Some 90% of drug candidates fail once entering Phase I trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A 2019 review of average success rates of clinical trials at different phases and diseases over the years 2005–15 found a success range of only 5–14% overall.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Separated by diseases studied, cancer drug trials were on average only 3% successful, whereas ophthalmology drugs and vaccines for infectious diseases were 33% successful.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Trials using disease biomarkers, especially in cancer studies, were more successful than those not using biomarkers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A 2010 review found about 50% of drug candidates either fail during the Phase III trial or are rejected by the national regulatory agency.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] For vaccines, the overall probability of success ranges from 7% for non-industry-sponsored candidates to 40% for industry-sponsored candidates.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] From discovery in the laboratory of a molecule with drug potential through the years-long process establishing an approved drug, the overall cost of development through all the stages of preclinical and clinical research is about $2 billion.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] In the early 21st century, a typical Phase I trial conducted at a single clinic in the United States ranged from $1.4 million for pain or anesthesia studies to $6.6 million for immunomodulation studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Main expense drivers were operating and clinical monitoring costs of the Phase I site.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The amount of money spent on Phase II or III trials depends on numerous factors, with therapeutic area being studied and types of clinical procedures as key drivers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase II studies may cost as low as $7 million for cardiovascular projects, and as much as $20 million for hematology trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase III trials for dermatology may cost as low as $11 million, whereas a pain or anesthesia Phase III trial may cost as much as $53 million.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] An analysis of Phase III pivotal trials leading to 59 drug approvals by the US Food and Drug Administration over 2015–16 showed that the median cost was $19 million, but some trials involving thousands of subjects may cost 100 times more.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Across all trial phases, the main expenses for clinical trials were administrative staff (about 20% of the total), clinical procedures (about 19%), and clinical monitoring of the subjects (about 11%).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] A Phase IV trial is also known as a postmarketing surveillance trial or drug monitoring trial to assure long-term safety and effectiveness of the drug, vaccine, device or diagnostic test.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Phase IV trials involve the safety surveillance (pharmacovigilance) and ongoing technical support of a drug after it receives regulatory approval to be sold.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The safety surveillance is designed to detect any rare or long-term adverse effects over a much larger patient population and longer time period than was possible during the Phase I-III clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] Harmful effects discovered by Phase IV trials may result in a drug being withdrawn from the market or restricted to certain uses; examples include cerivastatin (brand names Baycol and Lipobay), troglitazone (Rezulin) and rofecoxib (Vioxx).
[src:clinical-trials-design/phases-of-clinical-research] The entire process of developing a drug from preclinical research to marketing can take approximately 12 to 18 years and may cost about $2 billion.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A **placebo** (/pləˈsiːboʊ/ *pluh-SEE-boh*) is a medicine or treatment intended to appear genuine to its recipient, but which has no pharmaceutical effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Common placebos include inert tablets (like sugar pills), inert injections (like saline), sham surgery, and other procedures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebos are used in randomized clinical trials to test the efficacy of medical treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In a placebo-controlled trial, any change in the control group is known as the *placebo response*, and the difference between this and the result of no treatment is the *placebo effect*.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebos in clinical trials should ideally be indistinguishable from so-called verum treatments under investigation, except for the latter's particular hypothesized medicinal effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] This is to shield test participants (with their consent) from knowing who is getting the placebo and who is getting the treatment under test, as patients' and clinicians' expectations of efficacy can influence results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The idea of a "placebo effect" was discussed in 18th century psychology, but became more prominent in the 20th century.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Modern studies find that placebos can affect some outcomes such as pain and nausea, but otherwise do not generally have important clinical effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Improvements that patients experience after being treated with a placebo can also be due to unrelated factors, such as regression to the mean (a statistical effect where an unusually high or low measurement is likely to be followed by a less extreme one).
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The use of placebos in clinical medicine raises ethical concerns, especially if they are disguised as an active treatment, as this introduces dishonesty into the doctor–patient relationship and bypasses informed consent.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebos are also popular because they can sometimes produce relief through psychological mechanisms (a phenomenon known as the "placebo effect").
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] They can affect how patients perceive their condition and encourage the body's chemical processes for relieving pain and a few other symptoms, but have no impact on the disease itself.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The Latin term *placebo* means *[I] shall be pleasing*.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The definition of *placebo* has been debated.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] One definition states that a treatment process is a placebo when none of the characteristic treatment factors are effective (remedial or harmful) in the patient for a given disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In a clinical trial, a *placebo response* is the measured response of subjects to a placebo; the *placebo effect* is the difference between that response and no treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] It is also part of the recorded response to any active medical intervention.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Measurable placebo effects may be either *objective* (e.g. lowered blood pressure) or *subjective* (e.g. a lowered perception of pain).
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The placebo effect is a well-documented phenomenon, though it remains widely misunderstood and surrounded by misconceptions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Several studies have questioned its clinical relevance, fueling ongoing debate about its actual effectiveness.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A 2001 meta-analysis of the placebo effect looked at trials in 40 different medical conditions, and concluded the only one where it had been shown to have a significant effect was for pain.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Another Cochrane review in 2010 suggested that placebo effects are apparent only in subjective, continuous measures, and in the treatment of pain and related conditions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The review found that placebos do not appear to affect the actual diseases, or outcomes that are not dependent on a patient's perception.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The authors, Asbjørn Hróbjartsson and Peter C.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Gøtzsche, concluded that their study "did not find that placebo interventions have important clinical effects in general." This interpretation has been subject to criticism, particularly due to concerns about the adequacy of the methodology used.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Recent research has linked placebo interventions to improved motor functions in patients with Parkinson's disease.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Other objective outcomes affected by placebos include immune and endocrine parameters, end-organ functions regulated by the autonomic nervous system, and sport performance.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Measuring the extent of the placebo effect is difficult due to confounding factors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] For example, a patient may feel better after taking a placebo due to regression to the mean (i.e. a natural recovery or change in symptoms), but this can be ruled out by comparing the placebo group with a no treatment group (as all the placebo research does).
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] It is harder still to tell the difference between the placebo effect and the effects of response bias, observer bias and other flaws in trial methodology, as a trial comparing placebo treatment and no treatment will not be a blinded experiment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In their 2010 meta-analysis of the placebo effect, Asbjørn Hróbjartsson and Peter C.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] One way in which the magnitude of placebo analgesia can be measured is by conducting "open/hidden" studies, in which some patients receive an analgesic and are informed that they will be receiving it (open), while others are administered the same drug without their knowledge (hidden).
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Such studies have found that analgesics are considerably more effective when the patient knows they are receiving them.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A review published in *JAMA Psychiatry* found that, in trials of antipsychotic medications, the change in response to receiving a placebo had increased significantly between 1960 and 2013.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The review's authors identified several factors that could be responsible for this change, including inflation of baseline scores and enrollment of fewer severely ill patients.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Another analysis published in *Pain* in 2015 found that placebo responses had increased considerably in neuropathic pain clinical trials conducted in the United States from 1990 to 2013.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The researchers suggested that this may be because such trials have "increased in study size and length" during this time period.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Individual differences in personality traits may influence susceptibility to placebo and nocebo (negative placebo) effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] People with a more optimistic outlook tend to exhibit stronger placebo responses, while those with higher levels of anxiety are more likely to experience nocebo effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The administration of the placebos can determine the placebo effect strength.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Studies have found that taking more pills would strengthen the effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Capsules appear to be more influential than pills, and injections are even stronger than capsules.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Some studies have investigated the use of placebos where the patient is fully aware that the treatment is inert, known as an *open-label placebo*.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] If the person dispensing the placebo shows their care towards the patient, is friendly and sympathetic, or has a high expectation of a treatment's success, then the placebo is more effectual.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In 2008, a meta-analysis led by psychologist Irving Kirsch, analyzing data from the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), concluded that 82% of the response to antidepressants was accounted for by placebos.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] However, other authors expressed doubts about the used methods and the interpretation of the results, especially the use of 0.5 as the cut-off point for the effect size.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A complete reanalysis and recalculation based on the same FDA data found that the Kirsch study had "important flaws in the calculations." The authors concluded that although a large percentage of the placebo response was due to expectancy, this was not true for the active drug.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Besides confirming drug effectiveness, they found that the drug effect was not related to depression severity.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Another meta-analysis found that 79% of depressed patients receiving placebo remained well (for 12 weeks after an initial 6–8 weeks of successful therapy) compared to 93% of those receiving antidepressants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In the continuation phase however, patients on placebo relapsed significantly more often than patients on antidepressants.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A phenomenon opposite to the placebo effect has also been observed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] When an inactive substance or treatment is administered to a recipient who has an expectation of it having a negative impact, this intervention is known as a *nocebo* (Latin *nocebo* = "I shall harm").
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A *nocebo effect* occurs when the recipient of an inert substance reports a negative effect or a worsening of symptoms, with the outcome resulting not from the substance itself, but from negative expectations about the treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Another negative consequence is that placebos can cause side-effects associated with real treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Withdrawal symptoms can also occur after placebo treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] This was found, for example, after the discontinuation of the Women's Health Initiative study of hormone replacement therapy for menopause.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Women had been on placebo for an average of 5.7 years.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Moderate or severe withdrawal symptoms were reported by 4.8% of those on placebo compared to 21.3% of those on hormone replacement.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Knowingly giving a person a placebo when there is an effective treatment available is a bioethically complex issue.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] While placebo-controlled trials might provide information about the effectiveness of a treatment, it denies some patients what could be the best available (if unproven) treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Informed consent is usually required for a study to be considered ethical, including the disclosure that some test subjects will receive placebo treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The ethics of placebo-controlled studies have been debated in the revision process of the Declaration of Helsinki.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Some suggest that existing medical treatments should be used instead of placebos, to avoid having some patients not receive medicine during the trial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The practice of doctors prescribing placebos that are disguised as real medication is controversial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A chief concern is that it is deceptive and could harm the doctor–patient relationship in the long run.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] While some say that blanket consent, or the general consent to unspecified treatment given by patients beforehand, is ethical, others argue that patients should always obtain specific information about the name of the drug they are receiving, its side effects, and other treatment options.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] This view is shared by some on the grounds of patient autonomy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] There are also concerns that legitimate doctors and pharmacists could open themselves up to charges of fraud or malpractice by using a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Critics also argued that using placebos can delay the proper diagnosis and treatment of serious medical conditions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Despite the abovementioned issues, 60% of surveyed physicians and head nurses reported using placebos in an Israeli study, with only 5% of respondents stating that placebo use should be strictly prohibited.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In his 2008 book *Bad Science*, Ben Goldacre argues that instead of deceiving patients with placebos, doctors should use the placebo effect to enhance effective medicines.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] His concerns are that it is deceitful and that the placebo effect is unreliable.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Goldacre also concludes that the placebo effect does not justify alternative medicine, arguing that unscientific medicine could lead to patients not receiving prevention advice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebo researcher Fabrizio Benedetti also expresses concern over the potential for placebos to be used unethically, warning that there is an increase in "quackery" and that an "alternative industry that preys on the vulnerable" is developing.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The mechanism for how placebos could have effects is uncertain.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] From a sociocognitive perspective, intentional placebo response is attributed to the "ritual effect" that induces anticipation for transition to a better state.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A placebo presented as a stimulant may trigger an effect on heart rhythm and blood pressure, but when administered as a depressant, the opposite effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In psychology, the two main hypotheses of the placebo effect are expectancy theory and classical conditioning.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In 1985, Irving Kirsch hypothesized that placebo effects are produced by the self-fulfilling effects of response expectancies, in which the belief that one will feel different leads a person to actually feel different.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] According to this theory, the belief that one has received an active treatment can produce the subjective changes thought to be produced by the real treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Similarly, the appearance of effect can result from classical conditioning, wherein a placebo and an actual stimulus are used simultaneously until the placebo is associated with the effect from the actual stimulus.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Both conditioning and expectations play a role in placebo effect, and make different kinds of contributions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Conditioning has a longer-lasting effect, and can affect earlier stages of information processing.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Those who think a treatment will work display a stronger placebo effect than those who do not, as evidenced by a study of acupuncture.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Additionally, motivation may contribute to the placebo effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The active goals of an individual changes their somatic experience by altering the detection and interpretation of expectation-congruent symptoms, and by changing the behavioral strategies a person pursues.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Motivation may link to the meaning through which people experience illness and treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Such meaning is derived from the culture in which they live and which informs them about the nature of illness and how it responds to treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Since 1978, it has been known that placebo analgesia depends upon the release of endogenous opioids in the brain.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Such analgesic placebos activation changes processing lower down in the brain by enhancing the descending inhibition through the periaqueductal gray on spinal nociceptive reflexes, while the expectations of anti-analgesic nocebos acts in the opposite way to block this.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Functional imaging upon placebo analgesia has been summarized as showing that the placebo response is "mediated by 'top-down' processes dependent on frontal cortical areas that generate and maintain cognitive expectancies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In conditioning, a neutral stimulus saccharin is paired in a drink with an agent that produces an unconditioned response.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] For example, that agent might be cyclophosphamide, which causes immunosuppression.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] After learning this pairing, the taste of saccharin by itself is able to cause immunosuppression, as a new conditioned response via neural top-down control.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Such conditioning has been found to affect a diverse variety of not just basic physiological processes in the immune system but ones such as serum iron levels, oxidative DNA damage levels, and insulin secretion.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Recent reviews have argued that the placebo effect is due to top-down control by the brain for immunity and pain.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Dopaminergic pathways have been implicated in the placebo response in pain and depression.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebo-controlled studies, as well as studies of the placebo effect itself, often fail to adequately identify confounding factors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Placebos have featured in medical use until well into the twentieth century.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] An influential 1955 study entitled *The Powerful Placebo* firmly established the idea that placebo effects were clinically important, and were a result of the brain's role in physical health.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] A 1997 reassessment found no evidence of any placebo effect in the source data, as the study had not accounted for regression to the mean.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The placebo effect makes it more difficult to evaluate new treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Clinical trials control for this effect by including a group of subjects that receives a sham treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The subjects in such trials are blinded as to whether they receive the treatment or a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] If a person is given a placebo under one name, and they respond, they will respond in the same way on a later occasion to that placebo under that name but not if under another.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Clinical trials are often double-blinded so that the researchers also do not know which test subjects are receiving the active or placebo treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The placebo effect in such clinical trials is weaker than in normal therapy since the subjects are not sure whether the treatment they are receiving is active.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Cultural beliefs and religious practices can play a hidden role in how the patient experiences the strength of the placebo as well as the manifestation of it.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In many cultures, healing is performed through rituals with trusted figures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] These figures can span from clinical physicians to religious leaders.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Nevertheless, the strong belief in treatment, medically, spiritually, and socially allows for an increase in exhibiting symptoms.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Its main function is to give people and communities comfort and a sense of purpose.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Even while these advantages are subjective, they can have genuine a person or group psychological and social impacts, much like a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] However, religion is a difficult opinion to define and discuss since it lies in a gap between one's lived experiences and observable phenomenon.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] The different spirituality levels in individuals have been used to understand and predict how susceptible someone can be to a placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Religious practices or rituals such as prayers and meditation can activate brain processes that are closely linked to expectation and emotional control.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Since these processes are also involved in the placebo effect, they can be used to explain how belief can turn into something physical.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] It can also be argued that spiritual practices connect experiences to “top-down” mechanisms, where belief, emotion, and expectation can influence how symptoms are experienced in the body.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Cultural views about medicine can also pivot the mindset as a person's cultural background can shape their physiological and psychological journey prior to even receiving any form of therapy.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] For example, if a treatment aligns with one’s cultural and religious beliefs, they might be more reassured and willing to trust healthcare administrators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] These cases of optimism in expectation can increase the likelihood of the presentation of the placebo effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In some cases, even more than the treatment itself, with responses varying person to person.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] This goes to show that the strength of belief and social environment in shaping biological responses.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] At the same time, these effects are not always positive.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Positive beliefs work to strengthen placebo responses, but fear or negative spiritual experiences may contribute to the nocebo effect, where presentation of symptoms feel worse.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Anthropologists argue that culture affects the ways in which individuals perceive medication, from different rituals and methods of healing, leading to placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Hahn and Kleinman (1983) propose an "ethnomedicogenic thesis" of placebo, wherein the ethnomedical system generates a feedback loop: cultural beliefs influence the disease state produced and effective treatments reinforce the belief system.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] "Symbolic effectiveness," a term coined by Claude Levi-Strauss relating to Shamanism, can result in a placebo effect as symbols displayed by the Shaman provide the patient with a form of "verbal expression" that can create a healing response within the patient.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Apud and Romaní say that Shamans are a sort of psychoanalytical therapist, while many other cultural rituals and practices such as religion provide a psychological effect on the medical outcome of the patient, resulting in a placebo effect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] In Buddhism, Traditional medicine healers often prepared herbal remedies with blessed waters and string ties, performing chants of one's own culture to the people in a way of showing how ritual, belief, and medicine were a combined healing process.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] These practices, passed down through generations, have become integral to the empirical experiences of diverse communities.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Hyland and Whalley conclude that carrying out a ritual, rather than believing in the ritual, may be an important factor in long-term placebo effects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/placebo] Rituals are an attempt to "control nature," meaning that they can heal which results in the individual experience of placebo.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A **randomized controlled trial** (**RCT**) is a type of statistical experiment designed to evaluate the efficacy or safety of an intervention by minimizing bias through the random allocation of participants to one or more comparison groups.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In this approach, at least one group receives the intervention or process under study (such as a drug, surgical procedure, medical device or diet), while the other groups receive an alternative treatment, a placebo, or standard care.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs are a fundamental methodology in modern clinical trials and have been widely considered one of the highest-quality sources of evidence in evidence-based medicine, due to their ability to reduce selection bias and the influence of confounding factors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] However, they have also been criticized for failing to reduce bias in some cases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Participants who enroll in RCTs differ from one another in known and unknown ways that can influence study outcomes, and yet cannot be directly controlled.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] By randomly allocating participants among compared treatments, an RCT enables *statistical control* over these influences.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Provided it is designed well, conducted properly, and enrolls enough participants, an RCT may achieve sufficient control over these confounding factors to deliver a useful comparison of the treatments studied.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] An RCT in clinical research typically compares a proposed new treatment against an existing standard of care; these are then termed the 'experimental' and 'control' treatments, respectively.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] When no such generally accepted treatment is available, a placebo may be used in the control group so that participants are blinded, or not given information, about their treatment allocations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] This blinding principle is ideally also extended as much as possible to other parties including researchers, technicians, data analysts, and evaluators.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Effective blinding experimentally isolates the physiological effects of treatments from various psychological sources of bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The randomness in the assignment of participants to treatments reduces selection bias and allocation bias, balancing both known and unknown prognostic factors, in the assignment of treatments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Blinding reduces other forms of experimenter and subject biases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A well-blinded RCT is considered the gold standard for clinical trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Blinded RCTs are commonly used to test the efficacy of medical interventions and may additionally provide information about adverse effects, such as drug reactions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The terms "RCT" and "randomized trial" are sometimes used synonymously, but the latter term omits mention of controls and can therefore describe studies that compare multiple treatment groups with each other in the absence of a control group.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Similarly, the initialism is sometimes expanded as "randomized clinical trial" or "randomized comparative trial", leading to ambiguity in the scientific literature.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Not all RCTs are randomized *controlled* trials (and some of them could never be, as in cases where controls would be impractical or unethical to use).
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The term randomized controlled clinical trial is an alternative term used in clinical research; however, RCTs are also employed in other research areas, including many of the social sciences.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In the posthumously published *Ortus Medicinae* (1648), Jan Baptist van Helmont made the first proposal of a RCT, to test two treatment regimes of fever.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] One treatment would be conducted by practitioners of Galenic medicine involving bloodletting and purging, and the other would be conducted by van Helmont.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] It is likely that he never conducted the trial, and merely proposed it as an experiment that could be conducted.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The first reported clinical trial was conducted by James Lind in 1747 to identify a treatment for scurvy, and principles for conducting controlled trials were further elaborated by the Irish physician James Henry in 1843.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The first blind experiment was conducted by the French Royal Commission on Animal Magnetism in 1784 to investigate the claims of mesmerism.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] An early essay advocating the blinding of researchers came from Claude Bernard in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Bernard recommended that the observer of an experiment should not have knowledge of the hypothesis being tested.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] This suggestion contrasted starkly with the prevalent Enlightenment-era attitude that scientific observation can only be objectively valid when undertaken by a well-educated, informed scientist.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The first study recorded to have a blinded researcher was published in 1907 by W.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Randomized experiments first appeared in psychology, where they were introduced by Charles Sanders Peirce and Joseph Jastrow in the 1880s, and in education.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The earliest experiments comparing treatment and control groups were published by Robert Woodworth and Edward Thorndike in 1901, and by John E.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In the early 20th century, randomized experiments appeared in agriculture, due to Jerzy Neyman and Ronald A.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Fisher's experimental research and his writings popularized randomized experiments.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The first published Randomized Controlled Trial in medicine appeared in the 1948 paper entitled "Streptomycin treatment of pulmonary tuberculosis", which described a Medical Research Council investigation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] One of the authors of that paper was Austin Bradford Hill, who is credited as having conceived the modern RCT.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Trial design was further influenced by the large-scale ISIS trials on heart attack treatments that were conducted in the 1980s.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] By the late 20th century, RCTs were recognized as the standard method for "rational therapeutics" in medicine.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] As of 2004, more than 150,000 RCTs were in the Cochrane Library.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] To improve the reporting of RCTs in the medical literature, an international group of scientists and editors published Consolidated Standards of Reporting Trials (CONSORT) Statements in 1996, 2001 and 2010, and these have become widely accepted.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Determining the amount of information required to ensure informed consent can be difficult, and further research is necessary to determine the prevalence of and ways to address therapeutic misconception.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Placebo-controlled trials have been deemed unethical in instances where not receiving treatment may lead to harm for the patient, such as an aggravation of symptoms or risk of death.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Crossover trials, active-controlled trials, and other approaches have been used to mitigate this issue, though these options may not always be suitable for study, and have received their own criticism.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Active-controlled trials in particular may raise ethical considerations regarding clinical equipoise.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Although the principle of equipoise ("genuine uncertainty within the expert medical community... about the preferred treatment") is common to clinical trials and has been applied to RCTs, equipoise may be difficult to ascertain, and the ethics of RCTs have special considerations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] It has been argued that equipoise itself is insufficient to justify RCTs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] "Collective equipoise" may also conflict with a lack of personal equipoise (i.e., a personal belief that an intervention is effective), including that of the patient.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Whilst the above issues have resulted in robust practice guidelines around the conduct of RCTs, formulating balanced regulations tends to be difficult.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Strict protections may act in favor of indigenous populations, but could fail on a globalised setting, as their imposition urges the outsourcing of trials to countries with poorer standards and more economically vulnerable populations.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Frameworks which place great emphasis on patient well-being have also been criticized by some as paternalistic.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The RCT method variations may also create cultural effects that have not been well understood.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] For example, patients with terminal illness may join trials in the hope of being cured, even when treatments are unlikely to be successful.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In 2004, the International Committee of Medical Journal Editors (ICMJE) announced that all trials starting enrolment after July 1, 2005, must be registered prior to consideration for publication in one of the 12 member journals of the committee.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] However, trial registration may still occur late or not at all.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Medical journals have been slow in adapting policies requiring mandatory clinical trial registration as a prerequisite for publication.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] One way to classify RCTs is by study design.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] An analysis of the 616 RCTs indexed in PubMed during December 2006 found that 78% were parallel-group trials, 16% were crossover, 2% were split-body, 2% were cluster, and 2% were factorial.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs can be classified as "explanatory" or "pragmatic." Explanatory RCTs test efficacy in a research setting with highly selected participants and under highly controlled conditions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Another classification of RCTs categorizes them as "superiority trials", "noninferiority trials", and "equivalence trials", which differ in methodology and reporting.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Most RCTs are superiority trials, in which one intervention is hypothesized to be superior to another in a statistically significant way.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Some RCTs are noninferiority trials "to determine whether a new treatment is no worse than a reference treatment." Other RCTs are equivalence trials in which the hypothesis is that two interventions are indistinguishable from each other.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] There are two processes involved in randomizing patients to different interventions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Non-random "systematic" methods of group assignment, such as alternating subjects between one group and the other, can cause "limitless contamination possibilities" and can cause a breach of allocation concealment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] However empirical evidence that adequate randomization changes outcomes relative to inadequate randomization has been difficult to detect.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The treatment allocation is the desired proportion of patients in each treatment arm.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] However, no single randomization procedure meets those goals in every circumstance, so researchers must select a procedure for a given study based on its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] This is a commonly used and intuitive procedure, similar to "repeated fair coin-tossing." Also known as "complete" or "unrestricted" randomization, it is robust against both selection and accidental biases.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] However, its main drawback is the possibility of imbalanced group sizes in small RCTs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] It is therefore recommended only for RCTs with over 200 subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] To balance group sizes in smaller RCTs, some form of "restricted" randomization is recommended.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] "Allocation concealment" (defined as "the procedure for protecting the randomization process so that the treatment to be allocated is not known before the patient is entered into the study") is important in RCTs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In practice, clinical investigators in RCTs often find it difficult to maintain impartiality.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Stories abound of investigators holding up sealed envelopes to lights or ransacking offices to determine group assignments in order to dictate the assignment of their next patient.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Such practices introduce selection bias and confounders (both of which should be minimized by randomization), possibly distorting the results of the study.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Adequate allocation concealment should defeat patients and investigators from discovering treatment allocation once a study is underway and after the study has concluded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Treatment related side-effects or adverse events may be specific enough to reveal allocation to investigators or patients thereby introducing bias or influencing any subjective parameters collected by investigators or requested from subjects.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Some standard methods of ensuring allocation concealment include sequentially numbered, opaque, sealed envelopes (SNOSE); sequentially numbered containers; pharmacy controlled randomization; and central randomization.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] On the other hand, a 2008 study of 146 meta-analyses concluded that the results of RCTs with inadequate or unclear allocation concealment tended to be biased toward beneficial effects only if the RCTs' outcomes were subjective as opposed to objective.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The number of treatment units (subjects or groups of subjects) assigned to control and treatment groups, affects an RCT's reliability.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] If the effect of the treatment is small, the number of treatment units in either group may be insufficient for rejecting the null hypothesis in the respective statistical test.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The failure to reject the null hypothesis would imply that the treatment shows no statistically significant effect on the treated in a given test.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] But as the sample size increases, the same RCT may be able to demonstrate a significant effect of the treatment, even if this effect is small.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Traditionally, blinded RCTs have been classified as "single-blind", "double-blind", or "triple-blind"; however, in 2001 and 2006 two studies showed that these terms have different meanings for different people.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs without blinding are referred to as "unblinded", "open", or (if the intervention is a medication) "open-label".
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The *CONSORT 2010 Statement* is "an evidence-based, minimum set of recommendations for reporting RCTs." The CONSORT 2010 checklist contains 25 items (many with sub-items) focusing on "individually randomised, two group, parallel trials" which are the most common type of RCT.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Two studies published in *The New England Journal of Medicine* in 2000 found that observational studies and RCTs overall produced similar results.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] According to a 2014 (updated in 2024) Cochrane review, there is little evidence for significant effect differences between observational studies and randomized controlled trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] To evaluate differences it is necessary to consider things other than design, such as heterogeneity, population, intervention or comparator.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Like all statistical methods, RCTs are subject to both type I ("false positive") and type II ("false negative") statistical errors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Regarding Type I errors, a typical RCT will use 0.05 (i.e., 1 in 20) as the probability that the RCT will falsely find two equally effective treatments significantly different.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Peer review of results is an important part of the scientific method.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The study was able to accurately report that parachutes fail to reduce injury compared to empty backpacks.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The key context that limited the general applicability of this conclusion was that the aircraft were parked on the ground, and participants had only jumped about two feet.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs are considered to be the most reliable form of scientific evidence in the hierarchy of evidence that influences healthcare policy and practice because RCTs reduce spurious causality and bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Results of RCTs may be combined in systematic reviews which are increasingly being used in the conduct of evidence-based practice.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Many papers discuss the disadvantages of RCTs.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs can be expensive; one study found 28 Phase III RCTs funded by the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke prior to 2000 with a total cost of US$335 million, for a mean cost of US$12 million per RCT.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The conduct of an RCT takes several years until being published; thus, data is restricted from the medical community for long years and may be of less relevance at time of publication.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] It is costly to maintain RCTs for the years or decades that would be ideal for evaluating some interventions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Interventions to prevent events that occur only infrequently (e.g., sudden infant death syndrome) and uncommon adverse outcomes (e.g., a rare side effect of a drug) would require RCTs with extremely large sample sizes and may, therefore, best be assessed by observational studies.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A 2011 study done to disclose possible conflicts of interests in underlying research studies used for medical meta-analyses reviewed 29 meta-analyses and found that conflicts of interests in the studies underlying the meta-analyses were rarely disclosed.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The 29 meta-analyses included 11 from general medicine journals; 15 from specialty medicine journals, and 3 from the Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The 29 meta-analyses reviewed an aggregate of 509 randomized controlled trials (RCTs).
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Of these, 318 RCTs reported funding sources with 219 (69%) industry funded.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] 132 of the 509 RCTs reported author conflict of interest disclosures, with 91 studies (69%) disclosing industry financial ties with one or more authors.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The information was, however, seldom reflected in the meta-analyses.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Only two (7%) reported RCT funding sources and none reported RCT author-industry ties.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Some RCTs are fully or partly funded by the health care industry (e.g., the pharmaceutical industry) as opposed to government, nonprofit, or other sources.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A systematic review published in 2003 found four 1986–2002 articles comparing industry-sponsored and nonindustry-sponsored RCTs, and in all the articles there was a correlation of industry sponsorship and positive study outcome.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] One possible reason for the pro-industry results in industry-funded published RCTs is publication bias.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Other authors have cited the differing goals of academic and industry sponsored research as contributing to the difference.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Commercial sponsors may be more focused on performing trials of drugs that have already shown promise in early stage trials, and on replicating previous positive results to fulfill regulatory requirements for drug approval.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Whilst RCTs are considered the golden standard of research in evidence-based medicine, they may be inappropriate for study in certain contexts.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] For instance, RCTs may be improper for studying medical interventions with "obvious" benefits to patients, as such practice would unethically deny the control group of effective treatment.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Challenges may also arise in instances where a treatment requires the active participation of participants, such as psychotherapy or approaches based on community development.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Historically, it has been difficult to effectively utilize RCTs for the study of surgical procedures.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs may also be considered infeasible or unethical for studying the mental health impacts of interventions with obvious physical effects, especially when those are highly sought out by patients, such as with abortion and adolescent transgender healthcare.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Other than compromising masking, it is likely that RCT study designs for some of these interventions would also result in high likelihood of withdrawal, non-adherence, and response bias in the control groups, making RCTs potentially unreliable.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Due to the recent emergence of RCTs in social science, their application in these fields remain a contested issue among academics.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Some writers from a medical or health background have argued that existing research in a range of social science disciplines lacks rigour, and should be improved by greater use of randomized control trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Similarly, many economists have found RCTs are the *gold standard* for ensuring outcomes represent causal inference and not just correlation.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Overall, the adaptation of RCTs into social science has become significant in recent decades.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs have become a staple of identifying causal inference among microeconomic studies, particularly in development economics.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] In 1994, Paul Glewwe, eventual Nobel Prize winner, Michael Kremer, and Sylvie Moulin started one of the earliest RCTs in an economic setting by conducting a long run intervention in a school in Kenya, publishing the results fifteen years later.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Three years later in 1997, the largest field experiment in a developing context, the PROGRESA program in Mexico, was studied by a multitude of economic researchers.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The impact of RCTs on the discipline has only grown, as economists have found this method as a first-best approach to causal inference identification.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] While not at the forefront, the use of RCTs has helped to bolster the credibility revolution in empirical microeconomics, as well as becoming popularized as a result of the need for more rigorous identification.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Despite the shift towards using RCTs in research, there still remains division between economists on its use.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] List, a proponent of field experiments, particularly RCTs, finds that this method differs significantly from lab experiments, and therefore provide more robust measures for identification.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs also offer the advantage of providing true observational data that can be used where the absence of data would make it difficult to build a causal model with.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The American Economic Association maintains a registry of all active and completed RCTs within the discipline.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The registry is free to use and is designed to ensure researchers may share information with regard to on-going field work, as well as failures or limitations of study settings.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Since its founding in 2013, the AEA has tracked over 7,400 field experiments across 100 countries, with annual RCT registries growing year over year.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Researchers in transport science argue that public spending on programmes such as school travel plans could not be justified unless their efficacy is demonstrated by randomized controlled trials.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Graham-Rowe and colleagues reviewed 77 evaluations of transport interventions found in the literature, categorising them into 5 "quality levels".
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] They concluded that most of the studies were of low quality and advocated the use of randomized controlled trials wherever possible in future transport research.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Steve Melia took issue with these conclusions, arguing that claims about the advantages of RCTs, in establishing causality and avoiding bias, have been exaggerated.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A 2005 review found 83 randomized experiments in criminology published in 1982–2004, compared with only 35 published in 1957–1981.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] The authors classified the studies they found into five categories: "policing", "prevention", "corrections", "court", and "community".
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Focusing only on offending behavior programs, Hollin (2008) argued that RCTs may be difficult to implement (e.g., if an RCT required "passing sentences that would randomly assign offenders to programmes") and therefore that experiments with quasi-experimental design are still necessary.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] RCTs have been used in evaluating a number of educational interventions.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Between 1980 and 2016, over 1,000 reports of RCTs have been published.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] For example, a 2009 study randomized 260 elementary school teachers' classrooms to receive or not receive a program of behavioral screening, classroom intervention, and parent training, and then measured the behavioral and academic performance of their students.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] Another 2009 study randomized classrooms for 678 first-grade children to receive a classroom-centered intervention, a parent-centered intervention, or no intervention, and then followed their academic outcomes through age 19.
[src:clinical-trials-design/randomized-controlled-trial] A 2018 review of the 10 most cited randomised controlled trials noted poor distribution of background traits, difficulties with blinding, and discussed other assumptions and biases inherent in randomised controlled trials.
